"""
GPU-accelerated helpers for active SCEPTer simulation workflows.

Authors
-------
- Boris Sorokin <boris.sorokin@skao.int> AKA Mralin <mralin@protonmail.com>

This module remains part of the GPLv3-licensed SCEPTer project. The author
attribution above does not change the project-wide license.

Overview
--------
This module provides two publishable user-facing GPU workflows:

1. :func:`propagate_many`, a drop-in `cysgp4.propagate_many` replacement with
   optional GPU-resident execution and a session-first hot path.
2. True angular-distance helpers that follow the Vincenty-based spherical
   convention used by :func:`pycraf.geometry.true_angular_distance`, with
   explicit CPU, GPU, and auto-routed entry points.

The propagation backend keeps `pycraf`-style compatibility by default through
``gravity_model="wgs72"`` and ``ellipsoid_model="wgs72"``. Those controls are
split intentionally:

- ``gravity_model`` selects the SGP4 earth-gravity constants used to
  initialise TLE propagation
- ``ellipsoid_model`` selects the observer/geodetic Earth shape used for ECEF
  and geodetic conversions

Mixed configurations are supported for exploratory work, but they emit
filterable warnings because they are non-standard.

The canonical repeated-loop API is :class:`GpuScepterSession`. It keeps
reusable CUDA state, uploaded observers/TLEs, reusable workspaces, and
optionally compact GPU-resident intermediate results alive across repeated
iterations. The same active session can therefore chain:

- :meth:`GpuScepterSession.propagate_many`
- :meth:`GpuScepterSession.propagate_orbit`
- :meth:`GpuScepterSession.derive_from_eci`
- :meth:`GpuScepterSession.true_angular_distance`

without repeated device activation or unnecessary host round-trips.

Units and shapes
----------------
Unless explicitly documented otherwise, numeric angle inputs are interpreted as
degrees. Host-return angular-distance helpers return raw degree arrays/scalars
by default and optionally `astropy.units.Quantity` in degrees. Device-return
paths keep compact CUDA arrays on the GPU.

The propagation session API uses compact chunk-friendly shapes:

- ``eci_pos``, ``eci_vel``, ``geo``: ``(T, S, 3)``
- ``obs_pos``: ``(T, O_chunk, 3)``
- ``topo``: ``(T, O_chunk, S, 4)``
- ``sat_azel``: ``(T, O_chunk, S, 3)``
- ``sat_rotmat``: ``(T, S, 3, 3)``

The top-level :func:`propagate_many` convenience wrapper preserves
`cysgp4.propagate_many` broadcasted host-return semantics.

Satellite-frame conventions
---------------------------
For ``sat_frame="xyz"``, this backend follows the same right-handed satellite
frame as `cysgp4` ``calc_sat_iso``:

* ``x`` is aligned with the instantaneous satellite velocity vector
* ``z`` points toward nadir after orthogonalization against ``x``
* ``y`` completes the right-handed triad

This is the practical orthonormal form of the ITU-R SM.1413 Annex 1,
Section 2.3.1 reference frame, which describes the ``x`` axis in the
direction of the satellite orbit and the ``z`` axis toward the centre of the
Earth. That is the frame to use when interpreting or computing `alpha` / `beta`
style beam-pointing angles for ITU-R S.121 and S.368 style analyses.

For ``sat_frame="zxy"``, this backend matches `cysgp4` ``calc_sat_azel``:

* ``z`` is aligned with the instantaneous satellite velocity vector
* ``x`` points approximately toward nadir after orthogonalization
* ``y`` completes the right-handed triad

Auto-routing and calibration
----------------------------
:func:`true_angular_distance_auto` routes host-side work to CPU or GPU based on
an inexpensive per-machine calibration cache. The first relevant host-side
auto call can run a short CPU-vs-GPU micro-benchmark and store the resulting
threshold outside the repository. CUDA-array inputs and explicit
``return_device=True`` requests always force GPU semantics.

Warning policy
--------------
By default this module suppresses only the repetitive CUDA low-occupancy
``NumbaPerformanceWarning`` emitted for intentionally small grid launches.
That keeps notebooks and parser runs quiet without hiding broader performance
warnings. Set ``SCEPTER_SHOW_NUMBA_LOW_OCCUPANCY_WARNINGS=1`` before import, or
call :func:`configure_numba_low_occupancy_warnings`, to re-enable those
messages during GPU launch tuning.

Session lifecycle
-----------------
The long-lived workflow entry point is :class:`GpuScepterSession`. Sessions are
owner-thread objects: CUDA activation, cache eviction, prepared-context reuse,
and cleanup must all happen on the same Python thread that created the
session. Re-entrant activation uses ``with session.activate():`` scopes, and
the session can keep prepared contexts and reusable workspaces alive across
loop iterations.

Prepared contexts
-----------------
Prepared context dataclasses store both compact host-side metadata and matching
device mirrors. The session owns those device allocations and invalidates them
when caches are evicted or when terminal cleanup is requested. The recommended
entry points are the ``prepare_*_context`` helpers on
:class:`GpuScepterSession`.

Propagation and geometry APIs
-----------------------------
Orbit propagation, observer geometry, and true angular-distance helpers are
kept separate so workflows can reuse the most expensive intermediate state.
Propagation helpers work with compact chunk-friendly arrays, while the
top-level wrappers preserve `cysgp4`-style host-facing semantics when
convenience is more important than in-session reuse.

Sampler, pointing, and pattern helpers
--------------------------------------
The same session also caches angle-sampler contexts, S.1586 pointing grids,
antenna-pattern contexts, and atmosphere lookup tables. Those helpers share
the same activation and cleanup semantics as the propagation pipeline, so one
session can serve a complete step-1 / step-2 / direct-EPFD workflow.

Link selection and EPFD helpers
-------------------------------
Finite-cap satellite-link allocation, direct-EPFD beam materialization, and
exact pure-reroute service-curve sizing are implemented in this module so they
can operate on GPU-resident arrays without host round-trips. These helpers are
session-first APIs and assume that the caller is already working inside the
same owner-thread session model described above.

Cleanup semantics
-----------------
``session.close(reset_device=False)`` is the reusable soft-close path. It drops
cached device state but keeps the Python process ready for subsequent GPU
sessions. Bare ``session.close()`` performs terminal cleanup intended for
end-of-kernel or end-of-process teardown. With the current `numba_cuda`
runtime, same-process GPU reuse after the terminal path is not supported.

When idle eviction is enabled, the session records idle intent but performs the
actual cache eviction cooperatively the next time the owner thread re-enters
the session. Background helper threads never push or pop CUDA contexts and
never touch cached device arrays.
"""

